---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
---

<Base title="ExCSV Examples" description="Annotated ExCSV examples covering common use cases: minimal files, typed columns, aggregations, SQL companions, zipped containers, and more.">
  <h1>Examples</h1>
  <p class="intro">Real-world patterns showing how ExCSV builds on plain CSV. Each example is a valid <code>.excsv</code> file (v0.2).</p>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="1. Minimal" description="Just the header line. Everything else is standard CSV.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2
name,age,city
Alice,32,Berlin
Bob,28,Tokyo
Carol,45,Lagos`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">Any CSV reader ignores the <code>#</code> line and reads the data normally.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="2. Typed columns with constraints" description="Column schema defines types, validation rules, and display hints.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=1
#column name=id type=int unique=1
#column name=email type=string required=1 len_max=254 pattern=^[^@]+@[^@]+$
#column name=score type=decimal min=0 max=100 format=0.0
#column name=active type=boolean default=true
id,email,score,active
1,alice@example.com,92.5,true
2,bob@example.com,87.3,true
3,carol@example.com,64.0,false`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">Parsers can validate data against <code>pattern</code>, <code>min</code>/<code>max</code>, and <code>required</code> constraints.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="3. Tab-delimited with metadata" description="A TSV export from a database, with provenance metadata.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=tab header=1 encoding=UTF-8
#@source: warehouse_db.inventory
#@author: ops-team@company.com
#@exported: 2026-03-20T08:00:00Z
#@tool: pg_dump/16.2
#column name=sku type=string unique=1
#column name=name type=string
#column name=qty type=int min=0
#$dql-postgres: SELECT sku, name, qty FROM inventory WHERE qty > 0
sku	name	qty
WDG-001	Widget Pro	1200
WDG-002	Widget Lite	3400
GDG-001	Gadget X	870`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">The query that produced the file is preserved as <code>#$dql-postgres</code>. The raw text is taken to end of line — SQL syntax preserved as-is.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="4. Aggregations" description="Pre-computed statistics embedded in the file.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=1
#column name=region type=string
#column name=product type=string
#column name=revenue type=decimal unit=USD
#column name=units type=int
#%count_nonnull: 5,5,5,5
#%sum: ,,48250.00,1450
#%avg: ,,9650.00,290
#%min: ,,3200.00,120
#%max: ,,18500.00,520
region,product,revenue,units
North,Widget,18500.00,520
South,Widget,12000.00,380
North,Gadget,8750.00,210
South,Gadget,5800.00,220
West,Widget,3200.00,120`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">Aggregation lines use the file's delimiter. Empty fields mean "not applicable" for that column.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="5. SQL companions — single dialect via header" description="Set sql-dialect once, drop the suffix on every #$ line.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=1 sql-dialect=postgres
#@source: analytics_db.users
#column name=id type=long unique=1
#column name=email type=string required=1
#column name=created_at type=datetime
#$ddl: CREATE TABLE users (id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY, email TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE, created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL)
#$ddl: CREATE INDEX users_created_at_idx ON users(created_at)
#$ddl: GRANT SELECT ON users TO readonly
#$dql: SELECT * FROM users WHERE created_at >= '2026-01-01'
id,email,created_at
1,alice@example.com,2026-01-15T09:30:00Z
2,bob@example.com,2026-02-20T14:00:00Z
3,carol@example.com,2026-03-01T11:45:00Z`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">Each <code>#$ddl</code> line is one statement. They execute in file order. <code>#$dql</code> is informational provenance — never executed automatically.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="6. SQL companions — multi-dialect" description="Same data, three flavors of CREATE TABLE. Pick the one matching your target.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=1
#column name=id type=long unique=1
#column name=amount type=decimal unit=USD
#$ddl: CREATE TABLE orders (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, amount DECIMAL(10,2))
#$ddl-mysql: CREATE TABLE orders (id BIGINT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT, amount DECIMAL(10,2)) ENGINE=InnoDB
#$ddl-postgres: CREATE TABLE orders (id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY, amount NUMERIC(10,2))
#$ddl-clickhouse: CREATE TABLE orders (id UInt64, amount Decimal(10,2)) ENGINE = MergeTree() ORDER BY id
#$ddl-sqlite: CREATE TABLE orders (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, amount REAL)
id,amount
1,99.99
2,250.00
3,42.50`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">A consumer targeting <code>mysql</code> executes only the unqualified line and the <code>-mysql</code> line — others are skipped. The unqualified line acts as a portable fallback.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="7. Zipped container header" description="Header of the inner .excsv file inside a sales.excsv.zip archive.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma quote=double header=1 rows=10000 checksum=sha256:e3b0c442... original-size=204800 sql-dialect=postgres
#@source: warehouse.sales
#@created: 2026-04-01T08:00:00Z
#@tool: excsv-cli/0.2.0
#column name=order_id type=long unique=1
#column name=customer_id type=long
#column name=amount type=decimal unit=USD
#$ddl: CREATE TABLE sales (order_id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY, customer_id BIGINT, amount NUMERIC(10,2))
order_id,customer_id,amount
1,42,99.99
2,13,250.00
3,77,42.50`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">When packaged as <code>.excsv.zip</code>, the header carries <code>original-size</code> (uncompressed bytes) — it <strong>MUST</strong> match the ZIP central directory's <code>uncompressed_size</code>. The ZIP archive's comment field carries this same prefix so consumers can preview metadata without unzipping.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="8. No header row (header=0)" description="Columns defined by index instead of matching header names.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=0
#column index=0 type=datetime
#column index=1 name=level type=string
#column index=2 name=message type=string
2026-03-24T10:15:32Z,INFO,Application started
2026-03-24T10:15:33Z,INFO,Connected to database
2026-03-24T10:15:35Z,WARN,Cache miss ratio above threshold
2026-03-24T10:16:01Z,ERROR,Connection timeout on retry 3`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">With <code>header=0</code>, <code>index</code> is required. <code>name</code> is optional — the first column here is anonymous.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="9. Custom attributes (x- prefix)" description="Application-specific metadata using the x- convention.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=1
#@tool: my-crm/2.4.0
#@comment: Customer export for marketing sync
#column name=id type=int unique=1 x-crm-entity=contact
#column name=name type=string title="Full Name" x-crm-field=display_name
#column name=email type=string required=1 x-crm-field=primary_email
#column name=segment type=string x-crm-field=market_segment separator=|
#column name=ltv type=decimal unit=USD x-dashboard-widget=sparkline
id,Full Name,email,segment,ltv
101,Alice Park,alice@acme.co,enterprise|active,12400.00
102,Bob Chen,bob@globex.io,smb,3200.50
103,Carol Diaz,carol@initech.com,enterprise|churned,8750.00`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">Custom <code>x-</code> attributes are ignored by generic parsers but carry meaning for specific tools. Note how the header row uses <code>title</code> ("Full Name") for columns that have it.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="10. CSVW compatibility" description="Embedding a CSVW JSON-LD annotation alongside ExCSV schema.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=1 csvw=inline-json schema=excsv
#@source: hr_db.employees
#column name=id type=int unique=1
#column name=name type=string
#column name=dept type=string
#csvw {"tableSchema":{"columns":[{"name":"id","datatype":"integer"},{"name":"name","datatype":"string"},{"name":"dept","datatype":"string"}]}}
id,name,dept
1,Alice,Engineering
2,Bob,Marketing
3,Carol,Design`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">The <code>#csvw</code> line carries a JSON-LD payload. With <code>schema=excsv</code> (default), <code>#column</code> definitions take precedence; set <code>schema=csvw</code> to let the CSVW schema win.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="example">
    <CodeBlock title="11. Null handling" description="Default null (empty field) vs custom null marker.">
{`#!excsv version=0.2 delim=comma header=1 null=NA
#column name=sensor type=string
#column name=reading type=decimal
#column name=status type=string
sensor,reading,status
TMP-01,22.5,ok
TMP-02,,offline
TMP-03,NA,ok
TMP-04,19.8,NA`}
    </CodeBlock>
    <p class="note">Both empty fields and <code>NA</code> are treated as null. Without <code>null=NA</code>, only empty fields would be null.</p>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .intro {
    color: var(--color-muted);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }
  .example {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }
  .note {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--color-muted);
    margin-top: -0.5rem;
    padding-left: 1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-border);
  }
</style>
